And from the results of the last exams this year, we see that languages are leading the league table and have the highest score in the test scores in independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received a high grade of A.
Data from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students received A in Mandarin (a Chinese language), while 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners, and 63 percent of Spanish learners also received A.
This proves that in Scotland's independent schools, foreign languages are undoubtedly vital for children and young people in the future.
Nowadays, language subjects are in demand as well as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other educational institutions.
A survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that 17 percent of the reasons employers found it difficult to fill vacancies were language skills.
Thus, language skills are increasingly becoming the key to a successful future career for young people.
Given that more promising jobs require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what profession the student chooses, if he learns a second language, he will gain a real advantage in the future by learning another additional skill that will be useful to him throughout his life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who knows several foreign languages a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were not able to speak a foreign language well enough to support a conversation, and French was the only language with a two-digit percentage  15 percent of respondents spoke it.
That's why investing in language education is so important right now.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, there is a fairly wide distribution of languages taught in schools.
Some schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered most important to the UK in light of the country's future development by 2020  such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, independent schools will always have a choice of several languages with a teaching staff that is specialized in these languages.
Independent schools in Scotland strive to create an environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, regardless of what the future holds.
At present, there is no denying that languages remain vital to the future development of the country in the global business environment, and that this must be reflected in education.
