Ri did not mention the plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister focused on three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If this issue of denuclearization was the side of South Korea, not the United States, denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not be in such a dead end".
However, Ri's tone was markedly different from last year's speech when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea's missile targeting the US was inevitable after President Trump called Kim a suicide bomber.
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said that much more had to be done and that sanctions should remain in place until North Korea disarms itself.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn't set any time limits for the process: "Whether it takes two years, three years, or five months doesn't matter".
China and Russia believe the UN Security Council should encourage Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
