Harvard students are learning to relax in special courses
A new course introduced this year at Harvard University has helped all elementary school students learn to sleep more and fight the chauvinist culture of continuous caffeine intake to stay awake at night.
One academic found that the world's most successful students often have no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chesler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a clinical specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
After his discovery, he was inspired to introduce this course by giving a preliminary report on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning processes.
At the end of my talk, a girl came up to me and said, 'I'm sorry I didn't know about this until now, when I'm almost finished.'
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first offered to students this year, discusses how a healthy sleep habit contributes to academic and athletic performance, and how it improves overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's Health Services, says the university decided to introduce this course after it was discovered that students experienced severe sleep deprivation during the academic week.
The class lasts one hour, and students complete a number of interactive tasks.
One of the classes offers a picture of a bedroom where students, by clicking on coffee cups, curtains, exercisers, and books, get information about how each of these actions and substances  coffee, the light that causes sleep deprivation  affect sports outcomes, and how important it is to get enough sleep each day.
In another section, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The interactive campus map encourages the participants to reflect on their daily lives.
We understand that these classes will not change students' behavior immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know, as anyone else has a right to know, for example, how smoking affects their health, Professor Chesler added.
He said the false sense of pride in being able to "stink all night" is still common, and modern technology, along with the increasing pressure on students, means that sleep deprivation is becoming a problem.
He says that enough quality sleep is a student's secret weapon to fight stress, nervousness and anxiety, and even to fight overweight, because lack of sleep translates the brain into starvation, making it feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chesler develop the course by attending one of the classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to spread the word around campus.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all graduate students to go through a similar curriculum before entering a competitive institution.
Professor Chesler recommends that students set an alarm to warn them to go to bed and wake up, and to remember the harmful effects of blue light from electronic screens and LEDs that disrupt the human biorhythm and lead to sleep problems.
