Almanac: The inventor of the Geiger counter
And now the page of our almanac Sunday morning: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago on this day in Germany, the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm Hans Geiger was born.
Geiger developed a method of detecting and measuring radioactivity  an invention that eventually led to the creation of a device known as the Geiger counter.
As one of the foundations of science, Geiger's counter also became a staple of popular culture, and this was reflected in the 1950s film The Coronado Bell, starring cowboy-like Roy Rogers and Dale Evans as the seemingly unlike scientists in the lead roles:
Man: What kind of thing is that?
Rogers: This is a Geiger counter used to detect radioactive minerals like uranium.
When you wear these headphones, you can actually hear the effects of the atoms generated by the radioactivity in minerals.
I can hear you right now.
Hans Geiger died in 1945, just a few days short of his 63rd birthday.
But his invention, named after its author, is still widely used.
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to see abnormal cells.
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to see abnormally growing cells and kill them.
Part of the cure for the vaccine is to teach the immune system to recognize abnormal cells.
The method is to extract immune cells from the patient and alter them in laboratory conditions .
As a result of this change, the cells get the ability to see the type of protein that is typical of many cancers, and then the cells have to be re-identified.
The trial vaccine has shown promising results in patients with various types of cancer.
One patient who received this vaccine and whose immune system learned to recognize abnormal cells, ovarian cancer, has been in remission for more than 18 months.
The method involves removing the patient's immune cells and changing them in a laboratory setting, after which the modified cells can see the HER2 protein, which is characteristic of many cancers, and then the modified cells are re-inserted into the patient.
Professor Jay Berzowski, of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, says, "Our results suggest we have a very promising vaccine".
Professor Berzofsky explains: HER2 stimulates the growth of several cancers, including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancers.
A similar method has been successfully used in the treatment of leukemia, including fencing the immune cells of patients and teaching them how to affect cancer cells.
