National Trust is listening to the secret life of bats
A new study, conducted in one of the Scottish Highlands' estates, aims to show how bats use the landscape to search for food.
It is hoped that the data will give a fresh perspective on the behaviour of unique winged mammals and help in the future conservation efforts.
The study, organised by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will examine the common notturbo, the soprano notturbo, as well as the brown long-haired Dobanton bats and night-birds that inhabit Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special registrars will be installed at certain points around the site to monitor the activity of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
An expert sound analysis of all the recordings will determine the frequency of the screams and the types of activities that the various groups of these animals are responsible for.
A map of the habitat will then be drawn up and a report prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour on a landscape scale.
Rob Dwyer, NTS's conservation advisor, hopes that these results will show which habitats are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help identify the main areas of environmental management, such as the formation of meadows, and ways to maintain forest ranges in a state that is optimal for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and across the UK has declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened with extinction due to construction and development work that affects their habitat and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting systems can pose dangers, as can fly adhesive tape, chemical treatment of building materials, and domestic cat hunting.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, their nocturnal hunting habits are such that their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated eco-location techniques to accurately identify obstacles in the flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bat population issues very seriously.
The organization has ten trained experts who conduct surveys, field trials, and sometimes rescue work.
The organisation even set up the first and only bat reserve in Scotland at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten species of Scottish bats.
Real estate manager David Thompson says the estate is the perfect territory for them.
"Here in Threave, a great place for bats", he says.
There are old buildings, many old trees and all the elements of a good environment.
But there's still a lot that's unknown about bats, so the work we're doing here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to survive.
It reminds us of the importance of checking for bats before performing maintenance on private property, as accidental destruction of one nest can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young individuals, and possibly even the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected by law, and their destruction, harvesting or destruction of their habitat is illegal.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish bat conservation officer, is calling on the public to help.
She says, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we just don't know how many different species live".
